-- Foreign Investors Buy Net 3.92 Billion Rupees of Indian Stocks
-- B y   P a r e s h   J a t a k i a
-- 2012-06-18T13:22:24Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2012-06-18/foreign-investors-buy-net-3-92-billion-rupees-of-indian-stocks.html
Overseas  investors  bought a net  3.92
billion rupees  ($70.3 million) of Indian stocks on June 15,
raising their investment in the equities this year to 422.2
billion rupees, according to the nation’s market regulator.  Foreigners bought 25.3 billion rupees of shares and sold
21.4 billion rupees, the Securities & Exchange Board of  India 
said on its  website  today. Foreign funds sold a net 356 million
rupees of bonds, paring total inflow into debt this year to
203.5 billion rupees, the data  show .  They sold a net 3.47 billion rupees of shares last month
and 11.1 billion rupees of shares in April after being buyers in
each of the first three months of 2012. They put 421 billion
rupees in bonds in 2011.  Foreigners have invested 4.871 trillion rupees in stocks
and 1.411 trillion rupees in bonds since they were allowed into
the country in 1993.  India’s $1.1 trillion stock market,  Asia ’s fifth-biggest,
is influenced by flows from overseas. Flows surged to a record
in 2010, making the  BSE India Sensitive Index (SENSEX)  the top performer
among the world’s top 10 markets. The largest-ever outflow in
2008 led to the biggest annual slump of 52 percent.  The regulator provides data on shares bought and sold by
large investors, including trades in the primary and secondary
markets, with a delay of at least a day.  To contact the reporter on this story:
